SEAWEED BITES
  DATE : 2014-09-13
  TAGS : snack crackers
  TIME : 50
  SERV : 30 small cookies
  DESC
    & In the mood for something a bit different? These seaweed bites will do the trick! Highly addictive and sweet enough to have as a dessert.
    & The cookies were adapted from a recipe by <a href=\"http://www.food-sommelier.jp/recipe/R0123/173155.html\">Kiuchi Yuki-san</a>. 
    ? Rekka
  INST
    - Mix 1 tbsp of ground flax seeds with 3 tbsp of water. Let it sit until it thickens.
    - In a bowl, mix the 3/4 cup of flour with the 4 tsp of cornstarch. Mix well.
    - In a separate bowl, mix 4 1/2 tbsp of brown sugar, the 6 tbsp of coconut oil with 2 tbsp of soy milk*. Then stir in the flax seeds and water mix.
    - Put the wet ingredients with the dry ones, add 2 tsp of shredded wakame and mix well. <small>If all you have are larger wakame sheets, cut them into smaller pieces with scissors. They'll be hard to cut into shapes otherwise </small>
    - Form into a ball, put it in a bowl with a cover and stick it in the fridge for approximately 20 minutes.
    - Preheat your oven to 350F. After the 20 minutes is up, take the dough out of the fridge and flatten it into a rectangle with a rolling pin (or whatever you have on hand, anything cylindrical will work) to a thickness of about 1/2 a cm. Cut into whatever shape you want! I had small flower-shaped cookie cutters so i used that, you can easily just cut it into squares with a knife, it'll be just as delicious!
    - Prepare a baking sheet lined with parchment paper, bake for 15-20 minutes until they brown a bit on top. <small>Keep a close eye on them! Depending on how thin you made them and how strong your oven is they may brown quicker.</small>
    - Place on a cooling rack and enjoy!
